L SERVICE PREPARATORY\nI School. M.e. cor. 12th A F ata. n.w. Ph. Fr. 2080.\ni\nMUSICAL INSTRUCTION. _\nSTKEI. <IUITAR. rKI'I.BI.K, TAUtJHT IN\nsix Inwu. HAWAIIAN MfSIC STI'DIO.\nMonmouth Hotel. Franklin r>4i30. Apt. 30M. 3*\nWashington Conservat ory of Mnsic\nMAIN 7858 ALL BRANCHES\n1408 X. H. AVE.. AT PUPONT CIRCLE. 31*\nRAGTIME PIANO PLAYING. 10 TO 20 LE8Konn.\nguaranteed; note reading taught; demonstration.\n2 to 10 p.m. DBNART SCHOOL OF\ni POPLLAR MUSIC. 1408 H at. n.w. 30*\niminr nnnni run\nIKflUt fflUBLtraS\nTO BEQISCUSSEO\nSpeakers of World Reputation\nto Feature Meeting\nat Cleveland.\nCLEVELAND. March 2? {Special).?\nForeign trade problems of a wide variety\nare to be handled by men of international\nreputation at the coming\nconvention of the National Foreign\nTrade Council in Pl.v.lanH V4.... a\nto 7. While the program has been\nonly partially completed, in so far as\nspeaker* are concerned, the assignment\nof subjects for discussion to\ndate has marshaled an imposing array\nof authorities on financing, exporting\nIn general and the many\nquestions that are constantly arising\nin export trade.\nThe program as outlined by topics\ncovers practically all of the more important\nlines of industry contributing\nto our export trade. The first announcement\nof speakers selected inrl\nK-f I* t that the 1\nthe export field both from the viewI\npoint of the American exporter and\nthe foreign buyer. The latter feature\n1 will prove particularly interesting to\nj the exporter, and e?pecially to the\nmanufacturer who is just about to\nembark in the export trade.\nSpeakers and Topics.\nIn the general sessions these speakers\nand their topics have been announced\n\nWednesday. 11 a.m. \"Financing\nForeign Trade,\" Fred I. Kent. Bankers'\nTrust Company. New York;\n\"Frozen Credits?What They Are and\nHow to Thaw Them.\" W. P. C. Harding.\nFederal Iteserve Board. Afternoon\nsession?\"Value of Hong Credits\nto the Exporting Manufacturer.\"\nGeorge R. Meyercord, Illinois Manufacturers'\nAssociation; \"The Bumper\nExporter's Need for Bong Credit\nMachinery.\" J. J. Donovan, BloedelDonovan\nlumber mills; \"Credits and\nthe Export of Specialties,\" F. H. Taylor.\nS S. White Dental Manufacturing\nCompany.\nrnurauay, 10 a.m.?\"Government\nService to Foreign Trade.\" J. Walter\nDrake. Hupp Motor Car Company.\nFriday?10 am.?\"American Maritime\nPolicy,\" James A. Farrell, president\nof the United States Steel Corpoiation\nanil chairman of the National\nForeign Trade Council.\nGroup Sessions Attractive.\nPreliminary announcements for the\ngroup sessions show a very attractive\nschedule of addresses on many subjects\npertinent to both foreign and\nI domestic trade by leaders in our industrial\nlife.\nThe program is lacking particularly\nin the asignment of foreign speakers,\nwhich is expected to be announctd\nshortly and is only about two-thirds\ncompleted.\nFOREIGN BONDS.\nI Quotation* furnished by W. B. llibba 6 Co.\nPrice* at noon:\nBerlin 4* 14% Cormun gov. 4m.. 13%\nGreater Berlin 4* 14% German gov. B?-. 15\nBremen 4%*..... 18% Krupp 4* 18%\n?>*bleos 4m 18% Bad. Aniline 4%a 21%\nCologne 4* 17 Al. KI. (Set*. 4%a. 19\nl>anz1c 4m 18 Mein'ger Bank 4a 17%\nl>urm?ta<lt 4m 1H Nnrri. L. Bank 4a 17%\nI>r?-mleii 4? 15% Preuaa Bank 4?. 17%\nI>r#M<lcn 4%*.... 18% Berliner Bunk 4s 17%\n]>utfaeld<?rf 4m.... 18 Vienna 4s 3%\nK-wen 4* 18% Vienna 4%a 3%\nFrankfurt 4s.... IS Vienna 85\nFrankfurt 21% French 4s 4H\nHamburg 3-* 12% French 5s 57%\nHnrrlnir;; 3%s... 14', French Prem. 5s 4101 Hamburg\n4m... 18% British vie. 4a. ..311\nHamburg 4,.j>. 17V* Nat. war loan 5*.398\nKoeuigaberc 4*.. 15% War loan 5* 348\nIaeipzig 4%? 17% Italian 5m 33\nI^eipzic 18% Italian note* 1925 41\n(itirtuan gov. 3m.. 13 Ualgian Haul. oa. 70)4\nOnuan r?w. U Rolgl?? Praat. 5l 75\nBRISK EASTER 01\nBUT TRADE IN'\nPrice Level Continue\nEconomic Factor?I\nx: r\nhJi L UdllUll 111 v\n(Dispatches mnrklng thr progrru\nof thr deflation and readjustment\nprocess in business throughout thr\nrountry, Riving thr conclusions of\nMprrlnl correspondents. who hovr brrn\nliiNtrurtrd to prrarnt ronditlona and\nIndication* aa thr* realty rxiat, are\nprinted dally In The Star.)\nBY A. I). WELTOX,\nSjefial Pfopati-h to Thr Star.\nCHICAGO. March 28.?Brisk Kaster\nbuying in retail stores brought joy\nto the merchants and such charges\nof profiteering against florists that\nthey made public denial and explanation\nof costs. It was a straw, however,\nshowing the direction of the\nwind of public thought.\nThe ranging siuiauon nas Deen very\nlittle improved. '1. lemand for loans\ncontinues without ^oatement anil the\nlarger hanks leel the pull from their\ncountry correspondents, who are under\npressure from the reserve bank\nto force liquidation by farmers. The\nwarm weather has made the farmers\nunusually busy for the season and\nthey are indifferent about selling\nwhat they have to get funds to pay\ntheir bills. Liquidation will, however,\ncontinue, because the movement of\nprices downward must continue until\nUie readjustment is complete.\nSome Hopeful Signs.\nThere is a decided movement of\ngoods from producers and wholesalers.\nA manufacturer of catsup and\npreserves, who says he could sell\nnothing at any price in January, has\nsold Jh?,000 cases in the last six weeks.\nTnere is hopefulness along automotive\nrow not diminished by the rePort\nthat there are 100,000 men unemployed\nin Chicago. It must be explained\nthat Chicago is a great labor\nmarket and this season always brings\nlogetner nere an army mm wants\nfor the opening of work on farms,\nroads and railroads through the\nnorthwest. The extent of unemployment\nis not therefore a correct index\nof local conditions, in which, however,\nthere is 110 marked improvement.\nConditions Abroad a Factor.\nThe price level is tne nuit interesting\neconomic factor, and the most important\ntiling is mat prices are not\nlevel. It is the leveling process which\ncauses the present troubles. Business\nmen talk eagerly of the European situation.\nConditions abroad affect every\nline.'directly or indirectly. Failure to\nsettle wage disputes in England's coal\nmines will have an effect in Chicago\nas well as in Europe. A big steel corporation\nhere is keeping in as close\ntouch with that English conference\nas with the conditions of business reported\nby its salesmen.\nNever were the banks and business\nhouses giving so much attention to\nanalytic work. \"Care and conservation\nin business is the lesson we are learning.\"\nsaid a bank president. \"We are\ncoming down slowly but surely to a\nlevel of sanity and everything will be\nwell as soon as the new level is\nreached.\"\nNew York's Easter Trade\nin Excess of Period of 1920\nBY JAMES ALLGRTO.V.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK. March 28 ?A census of\nthe chief stores in New York at the\nclose of the Easter season shows that\nthe volume of trade was materially in\nexcess of that for the corresponding\nperiod of 1320, whether for the last\nfull week in March or for the week\npreceding Easter.\nIn tjjo stores t\\here statistical comparisons\nwe?e possible the increase\nwae estimated at from 10 to 25\nper cent. Most of them reported\na jump of approximately one-fifth. On\na unit basis this was not only most\nsatisfactory, but unexpected. On a\nprice basis, however, the showing was\nnot so gratifying, for not only were\nprices substantially below those of\nlast year, but the margins of profit\nwere still narrower. If profits should\nbe figured on replacement costs, it is\nprobable that this margin would be\nwider, for in most instances actual\ncoats have been employed, and the\nhigh production costs of last fall are\nrepresented in most of the stocks\nnow on the shelves.\nBuying Activity Continued.\nA more significant aspect of the\nsituation is that ail indications are\nof a continuation of buying activity.\nEaster is not the \"dress-up\" time it\nused to be. The 5th avenue parade\nyesterday was trivial compared with\nother days. The audience was huge.\nhut I tie performers tnemseives were\nfew. In other words, the weather\nitself Is now more of a factor In\na parade than the season, and this\nyear's activity was due rather to\nthe coincidence of the two than to\nanything else. The consequence, nevertheless.\nwas something more than\nreassuring and this morning's mails\nwere burdened with restock orders\nthat are bound to have their effect\non trade in general.\nOutside the apparel field conditions\ncontinue in a state of flux.\nThey may be hardening about the\nedges, but the heart of the mass is\nstill molten, and solidification is not\nto be expected before summer or fall,\nhopeful prophecies in some quarters\nto the contrary notwithstanding.\nWage Adjustment .Slow.\nWage readjustments here have not\nyet come within sight of the end. In\nthe city proper, for instance, they\nhave not yet affected the building\ntrades, although as individuals hun\ndreds of craftsmen have accepted\nless than their scales. Aft enfilading\nmovement has just hren started, however,\nand in Newark, the largest of\nthe communities adjacent to the\nmetropolis, the Ruliding Trades Employers'\nAssociation las announced\nthat for ten of the thirteen chief\ntrades with which it has agreements\nthere will be reductions ranging\nfrom 10 to 20 per cent, effective May\n1. This movement may be expected\nto spread until the city has been surrounded.\nThen, when nearby places\nof employment have been eliminated\nfrom the bargaining, the movement\nmay be looked for in the city itself.\nWhen it reaches here a good onefifth\nof the entire population will be\ndirectly affected.\nIncreased Auto Demand\nFrisco Revival Feature\nBY LYXJf C. SIMPSON.\nSpecial lhspatru to star.\nSAN FRANCISCO. Mai'ch 28?One\nof the beet signs of improving conditions\nin this district Is to be found\nin the increased demand for automobiles.\nJohn W. I.eavltt. one of the\nbest known distributors in California\nsaid:\n\"Business bus come back In a most\nconvincing fashion. After a period of\ndullness which lasted for some\nmonths there has been a sharp revival\nof demand. Throughout this\nentire territory this condition prevails.\nalthough In some sections it it\nmore pronounced than in others. Nat'\nI\" n t hrtoo unci Inn u tit h ar a Ornria\nare moving slowly the Improvement\nIs not So marked as In others.\"\nThis statement Is borne out by a\nnumber of other wholesalers.\nTrade mill Depressed.\nA review of conditions by the federal\nreserve bank of this district,\nwhich secured statements from more\nthan 140 wholesalers, showed that re.\ntail trade as a whole is still somewhat\ndepressed because dealers refuse to\nlake losses and restock at lower\nprices. In some lines, nowever, liquidation\nhas been completed and a distinct\ntrade revival bap followedAn\nannouncement by the Southern'\nJT IN CHICAGO,\nIME MAIN IS SLOW\ns the Most Interesting\niank Rush {or Loans.\n)ther Sections.\nPacific railroad of reductions of the\ncarload rate on wool by the Galveston\nroute to the Atlantic ports from\n$1.66', to SI.25 and $2.16 to $150\ni is construed as a warning that the\nrail lines are going make a fight\nto hold their transcontinental traffic\nagainst Panama canal competition.\nAlthough experimental shipments\nof apples and oranges and other per-\nishables by the canal route have j\nbrought good results, there is a feet-\ning among the melon growers and\nother shippers of highly perishable\nproducts that the railroads have a\n.distinct advantage for their use.\nt anners' Problem Disturbs.\nThe uncertainty of the canners la\nhaving a disturbing influence on the\nfruit situation. particularly for\npeaches. With the indications of a\nbanner crop, the growers are in\ndoubt as to their market. It in\nstated that some of the canners in\nthe interior have announced that\nthey would not operate this season.\nOne concern has offered to lease its\nplant to the growers, so they may\npreserve their crop. The growers\nnaturallv are Inclined to think this\ntalk is part of a bear movement to\nbring down prices.\nSignificant evidence of business re.\nvival was given here Friday, when\nthe state railroad commission refused\nto permit an increase in express\nrates on the ground that the business\nof the companies is profitable\nand getting better.\nB<\nmew rorK Move to Unite\nfor General Sales Tax\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK. March 2S.?A movement\nhas been started here to unite\nall individuals and trade associations\nwho favor a general sales tax as a\nsubstitute for some features of the\nfederal income tax now imposed. It\nhas been organized by the Tax\nLeague of America, with headquarters\nat 1270 Broadway, and the program\nincludes a \"campaign of education\"\nin every congressional district.\nHazen J. Burton of Minneapo EHfiNlttaMMrtCWHHfitoaM\nI\nI\nFor\nALCOl\nI septkpi\nthat isu\nIttrigor\nNon-Slip\nBottle\nwith the\nHandy\nStopper\nt,\nI\nAt Drug Stares\nand Toilet Counters\nruu JL uii\n$1 <k\n~i\nlis. president of the league, said today:\n\"Notwithstanding the complete\nbreakdown of 'the present system of\ntaxation, the tax experts who devised\nIt now propose to continue it\nIn operation, with some revisions and\nexemptions. But revisions and exemptions\nwill not meet the situation.\nA better, simpler and wholly new\nmethod is required, and the business\nman must lend his business experience\nin solving- his own tax problem.\n\"Effectively to aid the return of\nprosperity in this country, we must\npromptly lift from the shoulders of\nbusiness the blight of the present\nmethod of taxation by substituting\ntherefor a general sales tax.\nSome Possibilities Shown.\n\"It has been calculated by some\nof our soundest thinkers that a sales\ntax of 1 per cent on all business turnovers\nwould return at least $2,000.000,000\nin revenue annually. This\namount, nlu# that derived from n\nmoderate income tax and other ex- I\nlsting; sources of revenue, would furnish\nmore than the $4,000,000,000 required\nby the Rovernment annually.\nA sales tax would be paid by the\nwhole body of the people, but in infinitely\nsmall amounts by each individual.\nIt would abolish the present\nharmful method of class taction and\nxvould reduce the cost of livinR without\nreducing the profits of the producer.\"\nRanine** Note*.\nATLANTA. (Ja.. March 2S.?The\nSouthern Sash, Door and Mlllwork\nmanufacturers Association, emorac-\ning eleven states, has made public\nthe result of a questionnaire sent to\nfifty-three factories. The replies\nshow that orders run from fair to\npoor, but that inquiries are good and\nthe outlook for more building activity\nis favorable. In answer to a question\nas to whether rents, foodstuffs,\nfeed, clothing, shoes and wages had\ndeclined in proportion to the selling\nprice of millwork. eleven cities answered\nyes. and forty-two answered\nno. As a whole, the questionnaires\n\\ead to the conclusion that millwork will\nshow a steadily increasing demand.\nXi:w YORK. March 2S.?Ketailers\nin the jewelry trade report a steadily\nincreasing volume of trade, but the\nwholesalers have not yet begun to\nfeel the influence of the new movement.\nIt is claimed, however, that\nretailers are not heavily stocked, as\na rule, and that orders in the wholesale\ntrade may be expected soon. No\noverwneiming purcnases are anticipated.\nbecause the retailer is expected\nto move somewhat slowly.\nPrices in the trade have tended to\nharden rather than to recede, although\nin the inferior grades of diamonds\nthere has been a slight reduction.\nSilversmiths declare that\nsilverware prices have reached the\nbottom.\nBOSTON*. March 28. Interest of\n\n?>athn\n1UB is the same pi\n5, with no poisono\nropertks of alcohol,\nake ALCORUB w\n\nTODAY'S BO\nN?obot1cm reported to The Stop -o?r direct!\nNew York-Washington wire by Redmond A Co. 1\nCity of Parle 6a 1921 98%\nFt*nch government 8s 98%\nGovernment of Switserland 8a 10*\nKingdom of Belgium 7%s 96%\nU. K. of G II. and Ireland 5%s